R<193>m<193>ya<207>a and Mah<193>bh<193>rata, the two great epics ç
of India, have captivated the hearts of its people for several millennia. ç
Whether it is literature†both Sanskrit and  vernacular†arts,  crafts,  painting, ç
music,  dance  and  drama,  or  temple motifs, no aspect of Indian ç
culture has escaped the stamp of their influence. The simple village ç
folk who shed tears while listening to the ballads on the banishment ç
of S<200>t<193> or the highly skilled artisans working on the temple ç
motifs depicting the Kuruk<218>etra war, are both responding to a ç
dynamic and continuing culture of these epics.
Hindu tradition has always considered these two epics as itih<193>sa ç
(`verily did it exist thus') or history. Modern scholars have largely ç
conceded that the core of the epics could have had a historical basis.
@SB = Date and Authorship
@EMERGENCY = Reputed scholars, both Eastern and Western, have battled ç
for years to fix the date of the Mah<193>bh<193>rata war, also known ç
as the Kuruk<218>etra war. Incidentally this would also fix the date ç
of its heroes and, of course, their historicity. If the meti- culously ç
preserved Hindu oral traditions based on their notion of time as the ç
yuga- system are to be relied upon, the great war should have taken ç
place during 3139 <MS>B. C.<D> Writings of Megasthanes (312 <MS>B. ç
C.<D>) as also internal astronomical evidence corroborate this date. ç
Modern historians, however, have assailed this theory and are inclined ç
to accept a much later date, viz., 1424 <MS>B. C.<D> or 950 <MS>B. ç
C.<D>
Traditional lore ascribes the authorship of this epic to the great ç
sage Veda- vy<193>sa, also known as K<216><218><207>a Dvaip<193>yana. ç
He was a contemporary of the grandsire Bh<200><218>ma and had a firsthand ç
knowledge of most of the events described in the epic. Research-scholars, ç
however, feel that the original work called Jaya, written by Vy<193>sa ç
to commemorate the victory (jaya<|>=<|>victory) of the P<193><207><195>ava ç
princes over the wicked Kauravas, might have been a much smaller work ç
comprising about 8,800 verses. This was subsequently revised and enlarged ç
into Bh<193>rata, a work of 24,000 verses, by Vai·amp<193>yana, ç
a disciple of Vy<193>sa, and recited during the Sarpay<193>ga (serpent ç
sacrifice) of Janamejaya, the great-grandson  of  the  P<193><207><195>ava  hero ç
Arjuna. The final edition that has come down to us is the work of ç
S<220>ta Ugra·ravas, son of Lomahar<218>a<207>a (also spelt as Romahar<218>a<207>a), ç
and was recited at the Sattra-y<193>ga (a kind of sacrifice, the performance ç
of which is spread over several years) of the sage <185>aunaka in ç
the Naimi<218>a forest. It is this that has been called Mah<193>bh<193>rata, ç
due to the immense size (mah<193> = great) and its dealing with the ç
story of the people of the race descended from the ancient emperor ç
Bharata, culminating in the war. This edition is reputed to be `<185>atas<193>hasr<200> ç
Sa<221>hit<193>,' a collection of 100,000 verses, though the extant ç
text contains less. The round figure is obviously an approximation. ç
Some scholars have tried to establish that the epic has evolved over ç
a period of eight centuries (from 400 <MS>B.C.<D> to <MS>A.D.<D> 400) ç
to its present proportions. At the present stage of the research it ç
has not been possible to clinch the issue, and hence chronological ç
questions continue to remain open to discussions.
@SB = Recensions and Commentaries
Different regions of India have preserved different recensions of ç
the text of this epic. These have been broadly classified as the Northern ç
and the Southern recensions. Scholars opine that the latter which ç
is the longer of the two is more impressive because of its precision ç
andschematization as also its practical outlook. One of the standard ç
editions published contains 95,826 ·lokas or verses, in 18 `parvans' ç
or books, with 107 sub-parvans and 2,111 chapters in all, including ç
the appendix Hariva<221>·a. This just gives an idea of the immensity ç
of this epic poem, which is eight times as big as Homer's Iliad ç
and Odyssey put together.
Since the text contains quite a few riddles known as k<220><219>a·lokas ç
and vast portions  of  didactic  material,  several commentators have ç
tried their skill on it. The gloss of N<200>laka<207><219>ha (14th ç
cent.) is more well-known and is widely referred to.
