The Mah<193>bh<193>rata presents us with a veritable array of human ç
characters, from the sublime to the ridiculous. No type of human emotion, ç
no deed of valour, generosity, sacrifice or meanness is missed here. ç
Nor is there any artificiality in these portrayals. A brief delineation ç
of some of the more important characters may now be attempted here.
<185>r<200> K<216><218><207>a is undoubtedly the most brilliant and ç
picturesque personality projected by the epic. He appears on the scene ç
rather suddenly at the time of Draupad<200>'s svaya<221>vara (formal ç
selection of husband by a maiden princess), and continues to saunter ç
the scenes right up to the end. All his energies are channelized only ç
in one direction: protection of the right and the good, and punishment ç
or destruction of the wicked. His remarkable prowess, matched only ç
by the bewitching beauty of his perfect form, sage counsels, superb ç
stratagems and immensely superior statesmanship, captivate our heart. ç
There is absolutely no doubt that the epic projects him as God Himself ç
come down to save mankind, as he himself admits in the Bhagavadg<200>t<193>.
Bh<200><218>ma,  the  grand  old  man,  is another towering personality ç
that awes and inspires us, whether in the supreme sacrifice of abdicating ç
his right to the throne or the vow of celibacy or the matchless heroism ç
on the battlefield. It is but meet that <185>r<200> K<216><218><207>a, ç
who recognized his encyclopaedic knowledge and wisdom, has got it ç
