to unfold it. The <185><193>nti and the °nu·<193>sanika Parvas ç
are practically the repositories of his teachings.
Yudhi<218><219>hira, the eldest of the P<193><207><195>avas, is perhaps ç
the most dominant character of the epic, next only to <185>r<200> ç
K<216><218><207>a. He was not only a great hero on the battlefield, ç
true to his name (yudhi<|>=<|>in battle, sthira<|>=<|>one who is steady), ç
but a veritable incarnation of dharma or righteousness, a rare combination ç
indeed. That is why he is often addressed as Dharmar<193>ja (`the ç
monarch of righteousness') too. Come what may, he would never swerve ç
from the path of ethical uprightness about which his thinking was ç
always crystal clear. The Yak<218>apra·na-episode is replete with ç
the gems of his wisdom.
The epic pictures Bh<200>ma, the colossus and Arjuna, the warrior, ç
in more human terms.Ifdown-to-earthcommon sense characterizes Bh<200>ma, ç
Arjuna is more idea-listic and dreamy. However, both were extraordinarily ç
