Dro<207>a, the preceptor-warrior who was forced to take to the military ç
profession in spite of being a br<193>hma<207>a, appears a shade darker ç
than Bh<200><218>ma. Notwithstanding his learning and austerity, he ç
exhibited a streak of vengeful nature.
Vidura, the son of the maid-servant, is another personality who strikes ç
us not only by his sagacity but also by his intense devotion to <185>r<200> ç
K<216><218><207>a about whose divinity he had absolutely no doubt. ç
Here is a living example to show that it is not birth or caste that ç
makes for greatness but intrinsic character. His discourse to Dh<216>tar<193><218><219>ra ç
in the Udyogaparva is now well-known as Viduran<200>ti.
Duryodhana, the eldest of the Kauravas, is the chief villain of the ç
epic. His greed and jealousy overshadowed whatever heroism or virtues ç
he had, resulting in the near-total destruction of the two races and ç
untold misery to millions.
If the word `tragedy' needs any illustration, one should turn to Kar<207>a. ç
A victim of circumstances, his story can never be read with the eyes ç
